1
00:00:30,783 --> 00:00:35,783
Subtitles by explosiveskull

2
00:00:35,785 --> 00:00:37,985
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

3
00:00:46,385 --> 00:00:48,085
(MUSIC PLAYING)

4
00:01:13,118 --> 00:01:14,718
(DOG BARKING)

5
00:01:16,219 --> 00:01:17,586
MICHAEL: Yeah?

6
00:01:20,652 --> 00:01:22,886
No, no. No, we're leaving Cannes now.

7
00:01:26,719 --> 00:01:30,717
(SIGHS) Hey, Budapest could be huge for us.

8
00:01:30,719 --> 00:01:32,920
They say we'll cut
production costs in half!

9
00:01:35,086 --> 00:01:37,020
No, a vacation can wait.

10
00:01:41,619 --> 00:01:43,886
Yeah, Annie knows. She understands.

11
00:01:48,151 --> 00:01:50,950
Oh, right, I met with
Mr. Yamamoto this morning.

12
00:01:50,952 --> 00:01:52,950
He finally said yes to our deal.

13
00:01:52,952 --> 00:01:56,317
(CHUCKLING) Yeah. I almost
threw my back out bowing.

14
00:01:56,319 --> 00:01:57,686
(MICHAEL CHUCKLES)

15
00:01:58,085 --> 00:01:59,183
Okay, later.

16
00:01:59,185 --> 00:02:00,552
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

17
00:02:19,086 --> 00:02:19,916
Mmm.

18
00:02:19,918 --> 00:02:21,817
(INHALES SHARPLY) You have no idea

19
00:02:21,819 --> 00:02:23,682
how good this tastes
after seaweed and fish.

20
00:02:23,684 --> 00:02:26,149
Why can't the Japanese
distributors just serve croissants?

21
00:02:26,151 --> 00:02:29,050
I mean, we're in France, for Christ sakes.

22
00:02:29,052 --> 00:02:31,753
Can I offer you some delicious cold coffee?

23
00:02:33,219 --> 00:02:35,050
- Let me see.
- Oh...

24
00:02:35,052 --> 00:02:36,983
I gotta keep packing. (INHALES SHARPLY)

25
00:02:36,985 --> 00:02:37,985
Ooh.

26
00:02:40,085 --> 00:02:42,084
(DOG BARKING)

27
00:02:42,086 --> 00:02:43,450
You okay?

28
00:02:43,452 --> 00:02:45,383
- Oh, I'll be fine, it's just my ears, you know.
- (CLEARS THROAT)

29
00:02:45,385 --> 00:02:46,682
Right.

30
00:02:46,684 --> 00:02:48,350
Oh, come on, 100 camels?

31
00:02:48,352 --> 00:02:51,786
Where the hell are we gonna get
100 camels, for Christ sakes?

32
00:02:52,618 --> 00:02:54,216
What does the script say?

33
00:02:54,218 --> 00:02:57,717
Goats. I thought so. And those
Moroccan goats work cheap.

34
00:02:57,719 --> 00:02:59,050
You tell the director, no more creativity.

35
00:02:59,052 --> 00:03:00,683
He's gonna use the goddamn goats...

36
00:03:00,685 --> 00:03:02,818
And he's lucky he still has a job. Okay?

37
00:03:04,351 --> 00:03:07,315
Have I mentioned that
overseas production is a bitch?

38
00:03:07,317 --> 00:03:08,986
ANNE: Mmm-hmm.

39
00:03:11,252 --> 00:03:15,050
Seriously, 12 euros for a
bottle of water. (CHUCKLES)

40
00:03:15,052 --> 00:03:18,949
And look, they charged you for a
hamburger and a cheese sandwich.

41
00:03:18,951 --> 00:03:22,050
Well, I wanted a cheeseburger,
but I couldn't order one...

42
00:03:22,052 --> 00:03:26,816
So, I got both and I made my own.

43
00:03:26,818 --> 00:03:29,050
Honey, what are you working so hard for

44
00:03:29,052 --> 00:03:32,049
if your wife can't have a
cheeseburger when she wants one?

45
00:03:32,051 --> 00:03:33,950
Baby, I'd buy you a billion cheeseburgers,

46
00:03:33,952 --> 00:03:36,350
but you know how much I
hate wasteful extravagance.

47
00:03:36,352 --> 00:03:39,217
Ah, yes. Because your
cufflinks were such a bargain.

48
00:03:39,219 --> 00:03:41,819
(CHUCKLES) Have you seen that book I, uh...

49
00:03:43,985 --> 00:03:44,986
Thank you.

50
00:03:46,018 --> 00:03:48,617
Now let me check those little ears.

51
00:03:48,619 --> 00:03:49,816
So sweet.

52
00:03:49,818 --> 00:03:51,552
(BARKING DOG RINGTONE RINGS)

53
00:03:53,018 --> 00:03:57,050
Yeah. Okay. I'll be right down.

54
00:03:57,052 --> 00:03:58,986
Honey, would you call the bellman?

55
00:04:00,619 --> 00:04:02,085
Have him come up and get my bags.

56
00:04:09,219 --> 00:04:11,350
WOMAN: (OVER PHONE) <i>We're
sorry, all lines are busy.</i>

57
00:04:11,352 --> 00:04:13,315
- (WOMAN SPEAKS FRENCH)
- Ugh...

58
00:04:13,317 --> 00:04:15,085
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

59
00:04:16,619 --> 00:04:17,786
Excuse me.

60
00:04:19,086 --> 00:04:20,786
Oh, sorry.

61
00:04:22,318 --> 00:04:24,117
<i>Madame,</i> I'm so sorry.

62
00:04:24,119 --> 00:04:27,553
Would you please hold this under Lockwood?

63
00:04:29,952 --> 00:04:31,553
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

64
00:04:33,219 --> 00:04:35,949
WOMAN: (IN FRENCH ACCENT)
It was my real dream to act.

65
00:04:35,951 --> 00:04:40,049
And so I went to Paris seven years ago.

66
00:04:40,051 --> 00:04:43,350
And it was a wonderful experience.

67
00:04:43,352 --> 00:04:45,017
- It's a pleasure to meet you.
- Oh.

68
00:04:45,019 --> 00:04:47,083
MICHAEL: I enjoyed
talking to you. Good luck.

69
00:04:47,085 --> 00:04:48,585
Pleasure to meet you, too.

70
00:04:49,317 --> 00:04:50,686
Hi, honey.

71
00:04:51,217 --> 00:04:52,586
<i>Bonjour,</i> Anne.

72
00:04:54,085 --> 00:04:55,316
ANNE: Hello, Jacques.

73
00:04:55,318 --> 00:04:58,816
You're all set. I've checked
you out and the car is waiting.

74
00:04:58,818 --> 00:05:01,383
- You look lovely.
- She does, doesn't she?

75
00:05:01,385 --> 00:05:03,050
- Come on.
- (JACQUES CHUCKLES)

76
00:05:03,052 --> 00:05:05,686
Mr. Lockwood, can I have a photo?

77
00:05:12,318 --> 00:05:13,616
Thank you.

78
00:05:13,618 --> 00:05:15,085
Your driver is here.

79
00:05:18,851 --> 00:05:20,785
(INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

80
00:05:37,119 --> 00:05:38,686
I read the script.

81
00:05:39,217 --> 00:05:40,817
Yes?

82
00:05:40,819 --> 00:05:42,183
And I'm telling you, it
could be a little classic,

83
00:05:42,185 --> 00:05:44,050
and it's commercial, too.

84
00:05:44,052 --> 00:05:47,750
Classic and commercial?
Come on. Let's go produce it!

85
00:05:47,752 --> 00:05:49,817
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

86
00:05:49,819 --> 00:05:51,086
(IN ENGLISH) Only for a minute.

87
00:05:52,619 --> 00:05:53,986
What's the matter?

88
00:05:56,085 --> 00:05:57,085
(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

89
00:05:59,185 --> 00:06:00,619
What the hell?

90
00:06:02,651 --> 00:06:07,148
Oh, Michael, you know I am
not a whiner, but my ears...

91
00:06:07,150 --> 00:06:09,617
Oh, baby, I'm sorry. You'll be able to rest

92
00:06:09,619 --> 00:06:10,917
when we get to Budapest.

93
00:06:10,919 --> 00:06:12,553
And wait till you see where we're staying.

94
00:06:13,651 --> 00:06:15,616
- (CELL PHONE RINGS)
- (MICHAEL CLEARS THROAT)

95
00:06:15,618 --> 00:06:18,382
It's Mario. Uh, what's my inseam?

96
00:06:18,384 --> 00:06:20,083
34 inches.

97
00:06:20,085 --> 00:06:21,685
- 86 centimeters.
- Ah.

98
00:06:22,352 --> 00:06:23,786
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

99
00:06:25,818 --> 00:06:29,985
The food on the plane will not be
food. So I got you something good.

100
00:06:36,086 --> 00:06:37,950
Try this sausage.

101
00:06:37,952 --> 00:06:40,786
The old man in that shop makes it himself.

102
00:06:42,351 --> 00:06:43,718
Mmm.

103
00:06:49,084 --> 00:06:51,749
And look at this Dijon mustard.

104
00:06:51,751 --> 00:06:54,552
It's Edmond Fallot. The best in France!

105
00:06:55,819 --> 00:06:58,350
Anne, here are some drops for your ears.

106
00:06:58,352 --> 00:06:59,786
(JACQUES SPEAKS FRENCH)

107
00:07:00,619 --> 00:07:01,885
Thank you, Jacques.

108
00:07:03,952 --> 00:07:07,148
Our director in Morocco
has gone completely crazy.

109
00:07:07,150 --> 00:07:09,049
He's into double overtime every day.

110
00:07:09,051 --> 00:07:11,750
He seduced his leading lady but
now they're fighting on the set.

111
00:07:11,752 --> 00:07:15,016
It's a nightmare.

112
00:07:15,018 --> 00:07:18,817
(CHUCKLES) Yes, but he's
had three straight hits.

113
00:07:18,819 --> 00:07:21,350
Relax, we can trust him.

114
00:07:21,352 --> 00:07:22,886
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

115
00:07:24,684 --> 00:07:26,216
What's he doing now?

116
00:07:26,218 --> 00:07:27,553
I don't know.

117
00:07:29,217 --> 00:07:30,685
(JACQUES SPEAKS FRENCH)

118
00:07:31,619 --> 00:07:32,952
(MAN SPEAKING FRENCH)

119
00:07:49,351 --> 00:07:50,752
JACQUES: Mmm.

120
00:07:52,018 --> 00:07:53,949
- (IN ENGLISH) Smell that perfume!
- (GASPS)

121
00:07:53,951 --> 00:07:55,618
JACQUES: And it's full of vitamins!

122
00:08:01,318 --> 00:08:02,686
Mmm.

123
00:08:22,719 --> 00:08:24,083
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

124
00:08:24,085 --> 00:08:25,553
(GROANS)

125
00:08:26,384 --> 00:08:27,753
Ah...

126
00:08:30,351 --> 00:08:32,149
I can't believe Laszlo sent this.

127
00:08:32,151 --> 00:08:34,148
I told you he wants to
be in business with us.

128
00:08:34,150 --> 00:08:37,118
Be careful, because
he's not a generous man.

129
00:08:40,085 --> 00:08:41,717
- <i>Madame.</i>
- Yes?

130
00:08:41,719 --> 00:08:43,950
I notice your ears seem
to be bothering you.

131
00:08:43,952 --> 00:08:45,315
Well, yes.

132
00:08:45,317 --> 00:08:48,316
I must warn you that the cabin
pressure can be quite painful.

133
00:08:48,318 --> 00:08:50,248
I don't recommend you fly today.

134
00:08:50,250 --> 00:08:51,618
Thank you.

135
00:08:52,318 --> 00:08:53,686
(SIGHS)

136
00:08:54,751 --> 00:08:57,350
Michael, I think I should skip Budapest

137
00:08:57,352 --> 00:08:59,152
and just go straight to Paris.

138
00:09:00,351 --> 00:09:01,882
What?

139
00:09:01,884 --> 00:09:03,015
Yeah.

140
00:09:03,017 --> 00:09:05,349
I mean, you're gonna be
working the whole time anyway.

141
00:09:05,351 --> 00:09:08,816
Well, honey, I'm just sorry I
didn't know you were feeling so bad.

142
00:09:08,818 --> 00:09:10,315
May I make a suggestion?

143
00:09:10,317 --> 00:09:12,182
I'll take care of her.

144
00:09:12,184 --> 00:09:13,682
- Really?
- Yes.

145
00:09:13,684 --> 00:09:15,083
I have meetings tomorrow morning in Paris

146
00:09:15,085 --> 00:09:17,115
- and I'm driving back now.
- (PLANES FLYING OVERHEAD)

147
00:09:17,117 --> 00:09:19,982
Oh, that's fine. I can
take the train, it's fine.

148
00:09:19,984 --> 00:09:22,616
Everybody's leaving Cannes
today. The trains are full.

149
00:09:22,618 --> 00:09:24,849
- So, let me drive you.
- Uh...

150
00:09:24,851 --> 00:09:26,350
(STUTTERS) That's very generous,

151
00:09:26,352 --> 00:09:28,182
but you sure it's okay with you?

152
00:09:28,184 --> 00:09:29,349
Uh...

153
00:09:29,351 --> 00:09:30,683
You'll be there by dinner time.

154
00:09:30,685 --> 00:09:32,048
Look, I don't bite.

155
00:09:32,050 --> 00:09:33,382
(LAUGHS)

156
00:09:33,384 --> 00:09:35,850
- You rest up in Paris. I'll call you tonight.
- (BARKING RINGTONE)

157
00:09:35,852 --> 00:09:37,949
Baby, I love you. Uh...

158
00:09:37,951 --> 00:09:39,216
Hold on one second please.

159
00:09:39,218 --> 00:09:40,886
I gotta go. Bye.

160
00:09:42,250 --> 00:09:44,686
- ANNE: Michael!
- (MICHAEL TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

161
00:09:57,818 --> 00:09:59,183
This is a lovely car.

162
00:09:59,185 --> 00:10:02,782
- Yes. She's with me for a long time.
- Hmm.

163
00:10:02,784 --> 00:10:05,718
No, no, no, no. You need lunch. Come.

164
00:10:06,619 --> 00:10:07,683
- Oh.
- Here.

165
00:10:07,685 --> 00:10:08,853
(ANNE CHUCKLES)

166
00:10:10,852 --> 00:10:12,948
I like to stay here when I'm in Cannes,

167
00:10:12,950 --> 00:10:15,118
away from the crowd at the beach.

168
00:10:16,184 --> 00:10:17,685
It's a beautiful day.

169
00:10:19,718 --> 00:10:21,553
Are you nervous?

170
00:10:22,118 --> 00:10:24,052
Maybe. A little bit.

171
00:10:25,751 --> 00:10:28,350
We've never actually been alone together.

172
00:10:28,352 --> 00:10:31,315
(CHUCKLES) So you didn't believe
me when I said I don't bite.

173
00:10:31,317 --> 00:10:32,686
(LAUGHS)

174
00:10:33,685 --> 00:10:34,818
(WAITER SPEAKING FRENCH)

175
00:10:36,652 --> 00:10:38,082
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

176
00:10:38,084 --> 00:10:40,083
(IN ENGLISH) Uh, would
you like a glass of wine?

177
00:10:40,085 --> 00:10:41,349
Mmm-mmm.

178
00:10:41,351 --> 00:10:43,082
No, no.

179
00:10:43,084 --> 00:10:44,985
No, no. Thank you.

180
00:10:45,850 --> 00:10:47,616
Yes!

181
00:10:47,618 --> 00:10:49,182
When in France. (CHUCKLES)

182
00:10:49,184 --> 00:10:50,552
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

183
00:10:54,117 --> 00:10:56,951
You'll like this wine,
it's Chateauneuf-du-Pape.

184
00:11:02,618 --> 00:11:04,685
Ooh. That's good!

185
00:11:05,250 --> 00:11:06,652
(CHUCKLES)

186
00:11:10,619 --> 00:11:11,786
<i>Merci.</i>

187
00:11:14,684 --> 00:11:18,882
This wine goes well with your
ham <i>de</i> Bayonne and melon.

188
00:11:18,884 --> 00:11:19,884
<i>Merci.</i>

189
00:11:23,085 --> 00:11:24,085
Mmm.

190
00:11:25,818 --> 00:11:28,749
It's delicious! (GASPS) Mmm.

191
00:11:28,751 --> 00:11:32,849
I know it's rude, but, Anne,
I may have to take some calls.

192
00:11:32,851 --> 00:11:36,316
It's okay. I'm used to it.

193
00:11:36,318 --> 00:11:38,152
(CHUCKLES) You shouldn't be.

194
00:11:39,784 --> 00:11:41,383
(CELL PHONE RINGS)

195
00:11:41,385 --> 00:11:45,616
Anne, a deal offer is like a
souffle. It's all about timing.

196
00:11:45,618 --> 00:11:47,586
Yes, you don't want it to collapse.

197
00:11:49,784 --> 00:11:52,148
Yes?

198
00:11:52,150 --> 00:11:57,716
No, tell him I'm not in
unless the UK comes in for 30%.

199
00:11:57,718 --> 00:12:00,682
(SIGHS) Well, then, tell him to go to hell!

200
00:12:00,684 --> 00:12:01,952
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

201
00:12:04,084 --> 00:12:05,383
(IN ENGLISH) Okay?

202
00:12:05,385 --> 00:12:06,951
- Excuse me a minute.
- Mmm.

203
00:12:11,250 --> 00:12:12,619
(CHUCKLES)

204
00:12:19,851 --> 00:12:21,951
- (MUSIC PLAYING)
- (CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

205
00:12:39,618 --> 00:12:41,084
(JACQUES SPEAKING FRENCH)

206
00:12:46,950 --> 00:12:50,617
Anne, I need a credit
card. Do you have one?

207
00:12:50,619 --> 00:12:51,749
Don't you have a credit card?

208
00:12:51,751 --> 00:12:53,015
Oh, I have many.

209
00:12:53,017 --> 00:12:54,349
I explain later.

210
00:12:54,351 --> 00:12:55,686
Okay.

211
00:12:56,718 --> 00:12:58,949
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

212
00:12:58,951 --> 00:13:01,616
Just to hold the hotel
reservation until we get there.

213
00:13:01,618 --> 00:13:03,015
Did you say hotel?

214
00:13:03,017 --> 00:13:03,949
Yes.

215
00:13:03,951 --> 00:13:05,915
Jacques, we're going to Paris.

216
00:13:05,917 --> 00:13:08,182
Of course, of course, but you need rest.

217
00:13:08,184 --> 00:13:11,350
There is a fine inn with
an excellent restaurant.

218
00:13:11,352 --> 00:13:13,052
And it's truffle season!

219
00:13:14,750 --> 00:13:16,118
(CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY)

220
00:13:18,717 --> 00:13:20,982
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

221
00:13:20,984 --> 00:13:21,984
(CAR DOOR OPENS)

222
00:13:22,750 --> 00:13:24,083
It doesn't work?

223
00:13:24,085 --> 00:13:26,151
- I need to open the door for you.
- Oh.

224
00:13:28,750 --> 00:13:30,552
(GRUNTS) Yeah.

225
00:13:32,050 --> 00:13:33,617
(SIGHS)

226
00:13:33,619 --> 00:13:34,948
So how are your ears?

227
00:13:34,950 --> 00:13:38,248
Oh, I hope those drops
will help. Thank you.

228
00:13:38,250 --> 00:13:40,049
- (CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYS ON RADIO)
- Ah!

229
00:13:40,051 --> 00:13:43,215
Mozart, we couldn't do better.

230
00:13:43,217 --> 00:13:44,652
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

231
00:13:46,017 --> 00:13:48,982
So let's pretend we don't
know where we're going

232
00:13:48,984 --> 00:13:50,216
or even who we are.

233
00:13:50,218 --> 00:13:52,715
(LAUGHS) Oh, brother.

234
00:13:52,717 --> 00:13:54,118
(MUSIC CONTINUES PLAYING)

235
00:14:01,817 --> 00:14:04,551
Oh. You see that mountain over there?

236
00:14:05,683 --> 00:14:08,049
- ANNE: Yeah.
- It's St. Victoire.

237
00:14:08,051 --> 00:14:09,749
Uh-huh.

238
00:14:09,751 --> 00:14:11,884
Do you see that truck right in front of us!

239
00:14:13,850 --> 00:14:15,949
JACQUES: It's a major
landmark of this region,

240
00:14:15,951 --> 00:14:20,383
and a favorite subject for
many writers and artists.

241
00:14:20,385 --> 00:14:23,149
Cezanne captured it perfectly.

242
00:14:23,151 --> 00:14:27,716
I saw a beautiful exhibition of his
work last year in Aix-en-Provence.

243
00:14:27,718 --> 00:14:28,849
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

244
00:14:28,851 --> 00:14:30,815
- That's great.
- Yeah.

245
00:14:30,817 --> 00:14:32,049
Oh, it must have been incredible to see

246
00:14:32,051 --> 00:14:34,818
Cezanne's paintings here in this light.

247
00:14:35,084 --> 00:14:36,215
Yeah.

248
00:14:36,217 --> 00:14:37,583
(CHUCKLES)

249
00:14:37,585 --> 00:14:40,949
The ones that I know at the Met in
New York, they look a little sad.

250
00:14:40,951 --> 00:14:42,852
You know, as if they don't
really want to be there.

251
00:14:43,818 --> 00:14:45,618
(CLASSICAL MUSIC CONTINUES)

252
00:15:04,951 --> 00:15:05,748
(MUSIC STOPS)

253
00:15:05,750 --> 00:15:08,082
I like to stop about every hour.

254
00:15:08,084 --> 00:15:11,752
(SIGHS) Stretch my legs
and have a cigarette.

255
00:15:20,718 --> 00:15:23,085
It's been 42 minutes.

256
00:15:24,051 --> 00:15:25,552
Yeah.

257
00:15:31,684 --> 00:15:32,918
ANNE: Hmm.

258
00:15:34,085 --> 00:15:35,816
She gets thirsty.

259
00:15:35,818 --> 00:15:36,818
Ah.

260
00:15:38,951 --> 00:15:41,949
I hope my smoking isn't bothering you.

261
00:15:41,951 --> 00:15:45,948
Ah. Actually it reminds me of my father.

262
00:15:45,950 --> 00:15:49,116
He smoked two packs of
Camel cigarettes a day.

263
00:15:49,118 --> 00:15:50,785
He died at 56.

264
00:15:54,285 --> 00:15:56,815
Oh. See that hilltop over there?

265
00:15:56,817 --> 00:16:00,682
See those old stone walls and that castle?

266
00:16:00,684 --> 00:16:03,652
The Romans were all through this area.

267
00:16:05,818 --> 00:16:08,315
Did you know that this
region is called Provence

268
00:16:08,317 --> 00:16:11,616
because it was a province of Rome?

269
00:16:11,618 --> 00:16:13,682
- No.
- Yes. Ha.

270
00:16:13,684 --> 00:16:16,215
Michael and I have flown from
the south of France to Paris,

271
00:16:16,217 --> 00:16:18,382
but we've never driven.

272
00:16:18,384 --> 00:16:20,885
Driving is the only way to see a country.

273
00:16:23,950 --> 00:16:26,884
ANNE: I've always wanted to
see the lavender in bloom.

274
00:16:28,317 --> 00:16:31,649
(GASPS) It's gorgeous!

275
00:16:31,651 --> 00:16:33,684
JACQUES: I'll show you something.

276
00:16:36,250 --> 00:16:39,182
(JACQUES SPEAKS FRENCH)

277
00:16:39,184 --> 00:16:41,215
Anne, you know, I'm
happy to be here with you

278
00:16:41,217 --> 00:16:44,681
because it's the first time I've
come back here since I was a kid.

279
00:16:44,683 --> 00:16:47,248
ANNE: (GASPS) Oh, my God!

280
00:16:47,250 --> 00:16:48,948
Oh!

281
00:16:48,950 --> 00:16:51,749
- JACQUES: Yeah.
- (GASPS) It's incredible.

282
00:16:51,751 --> 00:16:53,816
It's part of an aqueduct
built when the Romans

283
00:16:53,818 --> 00:16:55,382
were at the height of their power,

284
00:16:55,384 --> 00:16:57,084
just to impress their subjects.

285
00:16:58,218 --> 00:17:00,048
- Well, I'm impressed.
- (CHUCKLES)

286
00:17:00,050 --> 00:17:02,051
- ANNE: Two-thousand years ago?
- Yeah.

287
00:17:03,185 --> 00:17:04,552
(CHUCKLES)

288
00:17:07,651 --> 00:17:10,019
They were great stonemasons.

289
00:17:26,684 --> 00:17:28,982
People canoe on this river.

290
00:17:28,984 --> 00:17:30,649
ANNE: Huh.

291
00:17:30,651 --> 00:17:31,916
That sounds fun.

292
00:17:31,918 --> 00:17:33,816
Yeah.

293
00:17:33,818 --> 00:17:35,648
I can't remember the last time

294
00:17:35,650 --> 00:17:38,016
Michael and I played
hooky for the afternoon.

295
00:17:38,018 --> 00:17:39,350
(ANNE CHUCKLES)

296
00:17:39,352 --> 00:17:43,316
You've got to taste the <i>noisette,
nocciola.</i> Mmm, it's great.

297
00:17:43,318 --> 00:17:46,982
(GASPS) And you must try the
<i>cassis.</i> And <i>fraise des bois.</i>

298
00:17:46,984 --> 00:17:48,817
(JACQUES AND WOMAN SPEAKING FRENCH)

299
00:17:50,985 --> 00:17:52,552
(JACQUES CHUCKLES)

300
00:17:56,951 --> 00:17:57,951
(ANNE CHUCKLES)

301
00:17:59,683 --> 00:18:01,084
That's pretty good.

302
00:18:03,684 --> 00:18:05,051
(JACQUES SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY)

303
00:18:07,352 --> 00:18:09,649
ANNE: Look, wild lupine.

304
00:18:09,651 --> 00:18:11,781
We have wild lupine in California.

305
00:18:11,783 --> 00:18:14,648
Oh, yes, but you can't eat them.

306
00:18:14,650 --> 00:18:16,915
Well, no. (CHUCKLES)

307
00:18:16,917 --> 00:18:19,684
(GASPS) Look at the wild dandelions.

308
00:18:24,783 --> 00:18:28,849
Mmm. With a little olive oil,
crushed anchovies, salt and pepper...

309
00:18:28,851 --> 00:18:30,816
- They make a marvelous salad.
- (CHUCKLES)

310
00:18:30,818 --> 00:18:33,382
I'm sure the Romans ate them.

311
00:18:33,384 --> 00:18:36,381
Does everything remind you of eating?

312
00:18:36,383 --> 00:18:38,685
- Yes.
- (BOTH CHUCKLE)

313
00:18:40,618 --> 00:18:42,919
Stay, please. The light is perfect.

314
00:18:43,384 --> 00:18:45,048
JACQUES: Mmm?

315
00:18:45,050 --> 00:18:46,083
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

316
00:18:46,085 --> 00:18:48,616
- Yeah?
- Turn a little.

317
00:18:48,618 --> 00:18:51,082
Oh, yes. Now come in close.

318
00:18:51,084 --> 00:18:52,685
It's great.

319
00:18:53,318 --> 00:18:54,684
Oh, yeah.

320
00:18:56,250 --> 00:18:57,951
(MUSIC PLAYING)

321
00:19:09,150 --> 00:19:11,082
(MAN SPEAKING IN FRENCH)

322
00:19:11,084 --> 00:19:12,817
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

323
00:19:24,351 --> 00:19:26,015
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

324
00:19:26,017 --> 00:19:27,951
- (CHUCKLES)
- (JACQUES CONTINUES TALKING)

325
00:19:52,683 --> 00:19:54,751
(SOFT PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

326
00:19:56,918 --> 00:20:01,182
This is Erik Satie. He
was a very eccentric man.

327
00:20:01,184 --> 00:20:03,785
Did you know he never washed his shirts?

328
00:20:05,084 --> 00:20:06,616
So, his wife did them?

329
00:20:06,618 --> 00:20:08,249
No, he did not have a wife.

330
00:20:08,251 --> 00:20:09,949
No?

331
00:20:09,951 --> 00:20:12,949
No, not everyone has to
have a wife to be happy.

332
00:20:12,951 --> 00:20:16,151
So, when his shirts got
dirty, he just threw them away.

333
00:20:34,284 --> 00:20:36,084
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

334
00:20:44,684 --> 00:20:45,849
JACQUES: Mmm-hmm.

335
00:20:45,851 --> 00:20:48,019
(BOTH CONTINUE SPEAKING FRENCH)

336
00:20:59,718 --> 00:21:01,818
(COUPLE SPEAKING FRENCH)

337
00:21:03,351 --> 00:21:05,585
- Jacques.
- Yeah?

338
00:21:06,118 --> 00:21:07,248
I'm not French.

339
00:21:07,250 --> 00:21:09,884
Yes, that is correct. Please.

340
00:21:15,084 --> 00:21:16,315
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

341
00:21:16,317 --> 00:21:17,615
(SIGHS)

342
00:21:17,617 --> 00:21:19,282
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

343
00:21:19,284 --> 00:21:22,948
Our dinner reservation is in
45 minutes. Can you be ready?

344
00:21:22,950 --> 00:21:25,084
- I'll meet you downstairs.
- Okay.

345
00:21:27,085 --> 00:21:27,885
(SIGHS)

346
00:21:29,817 --> 00:21:32,052
- <i>Bonsoir, madame.</i>
- <i>Bonsoir.</i>

347
00:21:42,684 --> 00:21:44,019
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

348
00:21:50,183 --> 00:21:51,815
Hi!

349
00:21:51,817 --> 00:21:54,616
MICHAEL: <i>I was thinking about you.</i>

350
00:21:54,618 --> 00:21:56,085
Yeah, what were you thinking?

351
00:21:56,951 --> 00:21:58,215
<i>About your sweet little ears.</i>

352
00:21:58,217 --> 00:21:59,314
(CHUCKLES)

353
00:21:59,316 --> 00:22:00,815
<i>So how's Paris?</i>

354
00:22:00,817 --> 00:22:02,749
I'm actually not there yet.

355
00:22:02,751 --> 00:22:04,648
<i>Why, what happened?</i>

356
00:22:04,650 --> 00:22:08,215
(EXHALES) Nothing, really. Jacques
wanted to stop for the night.

357
00:22:08,217 --> 00:22:09,685
<i>He what?</i>

358
00:22:10,084 --> 00:22:10,916
(SIGHS)

359
00:22:10,918 --> 00:22:13,781
Look, he's not the greatest driver.

360
00:22:13,783 --> 00:22:16,716
It's probably a good thing we're
not on the roads after dark.

361
00:22:16,718 --> 00:22:19,716
<i>Yeah.</i> (LAUGHS)
<i>Hey, don't forget,</i>

362
00:22:19,718 --> 00:22:20,951
- <i>he's a Frenchman.</i>
- (CHUCKLES)

363
00:22:21,684 --> 00:22:23,147
How's Budapest?

364
00:22:23,149 --> 00:22:26,782
<i>The hotel is great. It has an
amazing view of the Danube.</i>

365
00:22:26,784 --> 00:22:28,948
- <i>How are you feeling?</i>
- Better.

366
00:22:28,950 --> 00:22:31,214
Those ear drops are really helping.

367
00:22:31,216 --> 00:22:32,784
<i>What ear drops?</i>

368
00:22:35,818 --> 00:22:40,715
Michael, let's go on a real
vacation, just the two of us.

369
00:22:40,717 --> 00:22:43,949
<i>Yeah, my phone not invited.</i>

370
00:22:43,951 --> 00:22:45,949
<i>Honey, I think I'm getting
my back thing again.</i>

371
00:22:45,951 --> 00:22:47,685
<i>Do you know where my pill pack is?</i>

372
00:22:49,650 --> 00:22:50,983
It's in the pocket of your kit.

373
00:22:50,985 --> 00:22:52,085
<i>I looked there.</i>

374
00:22:53,751 --> 00:22:55,215
It's on the inside zip one.

375
00:22:55,217 --> 00:22:57,083
<i>Okay, thanks.</i>

376
00:22:57,085 --> 00:22:58,416
<i>You're the best.</i>

377
00:22:58,418 --> 00:23:00,952
<i>Uh, what time do you think
you'll get to Paris tomorrow?</i>

378
00:23:02,084 --> 00:23:03,949
Early afternoon, I guess.

379
00:23:03,951 --> 00:23:06,815
<i>Okay. Call me when you
get there. Love you.</i>

380
00:23:06,817 --> 00:23:08,684
All right. Love you, too.

381
00:23:12,984 --> 00:23:13,984
(SIGHS)

382
00:23:31,350 --> 00:23:32,949
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

383
00:23:32,951 --> 00:23:34,649
I'm sorry, I don't speak French.

384
00:23:34,651 --> 00:23:36,552
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

385
00:23:37,217 --> 00:23:38,552
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

386
00:23:40,017 --> 00:23:42,048
I'm sorry. What did he say?

387
00:23:42,050 --> 00:23:44,919
He said, "You're very lucky to
be having dinner with Jacques."

388
00:23:45,651 --> 00:23:47,215
ANNE: (LAUGHS) Oh.

389
00:23:47,217 --> 00:23:50,682
The chef here was famous
for roast baby lamb.

390
00:23:50,684 --> 00:23:52,615
What looks good to you, Anne?

391
00:23:52,617 --> 00:23:53,784
Oh...

392
00:23:56,050 --> 00:23:59,348
Everything looks good. I can't decide.

393
00:23:59,350 --> 00:24:01,348
You don't have to.

394
00:24:01,350 --> 00:24:04,784
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

395
00:24:25,016 --> 00:24:26,951
- I'm full already.
- (CHUCKLES)

396
00:24:27,717 --> 00:24:29,885
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

397
00:24:43,351 --> 00:24:46,348
The wines of the region
are Condrieu and Cote-Rotie.

398
00:24:46,350 --> 00:24:47,952
We'll have them both.

399
00:24:50,150 --> 00:24:52,082
(SOFT PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

400
00:24:52,084 --> 00:24:53,616
(JAQCUES SPEAKS FRENCH)

401
00:24:53,618 --> 00:24:54,885
(WAITER SPEAKING FRENCH)

402
00:25:03,784 --> 00:25:05,051
This looks great!

403
00:25:06,618 --> 00:25:08,082
JACQUES: Mmm.

404
00:25:08,084 --> 00:25:09,248
Mmm.

405
00:25:09,250 --> 00:25:12,148
So, Michael tells me you've
closed your dress shop.

406
00:25:12,150 --> 00:25:15,348
Yes. My partner moved to
London with her husband.

407
00:25:15,350 --> 00:25:17,949
- I couldn't keep it open by myself.
- Do you miss it?

408
00:25:17,951 --> 00:25:21,349
I miss our customers and
all the pretty clothes.

409
00:25:21,351 --> 00:25:23,616
But I'm ready to try something new.

410
00:25:23,618 --> 00:25:24,947
What interests you now?

411
00:25:24,949 --> 00:25:26,816
I notice you take a lot of pictures.

412
00:25:26,818 --> 00:25:28,948
Oh. Those are just for fun.

413
00:25:28,950 --> 00:25:31,314
I started taking photos
for our shop announcements.

414
00:25:31,316 --> 00:25:33,081
JACQUES: Mmm-hmm.

415
00:25:33,083 --> 00:25:35,147
And now I can't stop.

416
00:25:35,149 --> 00:25:36,150
(ANNE CHUCKLES)

417
00:25:37,184 --> 00:25:38,551
(JACQUES CHUCKLES LIGHTLY)

418
00:25:39,984 --> 00:25:40,984
Now.

419
00:25:42,083 --> 00:25:43,851
- (LAUGHS)
- Eh?

420
00:25:46,617 --> 00:25:48,084
- Another one.
- (LAUGHS) Oh.

421
00:25:51,949 --> 00:25:53,552
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

422
00:26:00,683 --> 00:26:05,082
I did this with our daughter,
Alexandra, when she was little.

423
00:26:05,084 --> 00:26:08,615
I remember her. She liked
to wear your red shoes.

424
00:26:08,617 --> 00:26:09,849
You remember that?

425
00:26:09,851 --> 00:26:10,947
Yeah.

426
00:26:10,949 --> 00:26:12,884
- I still have those shoes.
- (CHUCKLES)

427
00:26:14,050 --> 00:26:16,684
So when was the last time you wore them?

428
00:26:17,651 --> 00:26:19,082
How old is she now?

429
00:26:19,084 --> 00:26:20,181
(SIGHS)

430
00:26:20,183 --> 00:26:22,348
She's 18.

431
00:26:22,350 --> 00:26:26,815
Here's a picture of her high
school graduation. (CHUCKLES)

432
00:26:26,817 --> 00:26:28,849
She's at U.C. Santa Barbara, now.

433
00:26:28,851 --> 00:26:31,947
It's her second semester away from home.

434
00:26:31,949 --> 00:26:33,214
JACQUES: She has lovely eyes...

435
00:26:33,216 --> 00:26:34,382
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

436
00:26:34,384 --> 00:26:36,114
(IN ENGLISH) Like her mother.

437
00:26:36,116 --> 00:26:39,681
Her mother is so used to juggling
work and taking care of her...

438
00:26:39,683 --> 00:26:41,947
I don't know what I'm gonna do with myself.

439
00:26:41,949 --> 00:26:43,648
But you have so much to offer.

440
00:26:43,650 --> 00:26:45,584
It's a great time for you now.

441
00:26:46,683 --> 00:26:48,215
- It is?
- Yes, of course.

442
00:26:48,217 --> 00:26:49,616
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

443
00:26:49,618 --> 00:26:51,947
What makes you dance in the street?

444
00:26:51,949 --> 00:26:54,716
You're beautiful. You're
an interesting woman.

445
00:26:54,718 --> 00:26:56,349
Oh, come on.

446
00:26:56,351 --> 00:26:58,982
I saw all the men in Cannes
drooling over those young girls.

447
00:26:58,984 --> 00:27:00,682
(SCOFFS) Come on. They're just Pop-Tarts.

448
00:27:00,684 --> 00:27:03,881
You, you're chocolate creme brulee.

449
00:27:03,883 --> 00:27:05,215
Yes, that's you. Brulee.

450
00:27:05,217 --> 00:27:06,848
(LAUGHS)

451
00:27:06,850 --> 00:27:08,785
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

452
00:27:13,049 --> 00:27:15,716
(IN ENGLISH) Oh, let me
introduce you to Anne.

453
00:27:15,718 --> 00:27:17,047
- This is Carole.
- Nice to meet you.

454
00:27:17,049 --> 00:27:18,616
- Nice to meet you.
- Sorry for intruding.

455
00:27:18,618 --> 00:27:20,048
I just heard that Jacques was here.

456
00:27:20,050 --> 00:27:21,884
(BOTH CONTINUE SPEAKING FRENCH)

457
00:27:32,117 --> 00:27:33,214
Enjoy your dinner.

458
00:27:33,216 --> 00:27:34,551
Thank you.

459
00:27:41,083 --> 00:27:44,082
I used to come here. I got to know Carole.

460
00:27:44,084 --> 00:27:46,081
Yeah, that was clear.

461
00:27:46,083 --> 00:27:47,682
She's the owner's niece.

462
00:27:47,684 --> 00:27:48,851
- Of course.
- (CHUCKLES)

463
00:27:51,017 --> 00:27:53,782
Why do flowers smell
so much better in France

464
00:27:53,784 --> 00:27:54,947
than they do in the US?

465
00:27:54,949 --> 00:27:56,648
Why? Because we're in France.

466
00:27:56,650 --> 00:27:58,147
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

467
00:27:58,149 --> 00:28:02,215
In America they look lovely but
they smell like a refrigerator.

468
00:28:02,217 --> 00:28:04,215
- It's true.
- Yeah.

469
00:28:04,217 --> 00:28:05,681
Well...

470
00:28:05,683 --> 00:28:07,349
(SIGHS) Roses are my favorite.

471
00:28:07,351 --> 00:28:10,948
Yes, but their scent mustn't
intrude on the aroma of the wine.

472
00:28:10,950 --> 00:28:12,752
- Ah.
- (WAITER SPEAKS FRENCH)

473
00:28:14,383 --> 00:28:15,751
Mmm-hmm.

474
00:28:16,717 --> 00:28:17,780
(SIGHS DEEPLY)

475
00:28:17,782 --> 00:28:19,717
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

476
00:28:23,017 --> 00:28:25,314
Did you know that it was the Romans

477
00:28:25,316 --> 00:28:28,081
who started winemaking in France?

478
00:28:28,083 --> 00:28:30,981
I did not know that, my tour guide.

479
00:28:30,983 --> 00:28:32,050
(CHUCKLES)

480
00:28:37,184 --> 00:28:38,551
(SNIFFS)

481
00:28:42,084 --> 00:28:43,114
Mmm.

482
00:28:43,116 --> 00:28:44,747
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

483
00:28:44,749 --> 00:28:46,947
- Ooh, la, la?
- (JACQUES CHUCKLES)

484
00:28:46,949 --> 00:28:47,950
You'll see.

485
00:28:49,684 --> 00:28:50,851
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

486
00:28:56,817 --> 00:28:59,552
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

487
00:29:03,850 --> 00:29:06,214
So <i>dorade royale</i>
is what you call snapper.

488
00:29:06,216 --> 00:29:08,348
- Mmm-hmm.
- It has little teeth like a baby

489
00:29:08,350 --> 00:29:10,684
and it comes from the Atlantic.

490
00:29:12,984 --> 00:29:14,048
Mmm.

491
00:29:14,050 --> 00:29:16,081
Mmm. That's a pretty dress, Brulee.

492
00:29:16,083 --> 00:29:17,615
Is it from your store?

493
00:29:17,617 --> 00:29:20,047
- Actually, it's French.
- Oh.

494
00:29:20,049 --> 00:29:22,715
Normally I have a passion for textiles.

495
00:29:22,717 --> 00:29:25,051
And what else do you have a passion for?

496
00:29:26,849 --> 00:29:28,615
Very expensive jewelry.

497
00:29:28,617 --> 00:29:29,981
Ah.

498
00:29:29,983 --> 00:29:33,083
Yeah, like that, uh, fancy
bracelet I see you wearing.

499
00:29:34,216 --> 00:29:35,783
Oh. (CHUCKLES)

500
00:29:38,317 --> 00:29:40,148
That.

501
00:29:40,150 --> 00:29:44,147
Actually this was given to
me by a chef in Barcelona.

502
00:29:44,149 --> 00:29:49,282
We ate the best seafood in the
world. Fresh barnacles, giant crabs.

503
00:29:49,284 --> 00:29:53,214
He wore it to remind himself
of his humble beginnings,

504
00:29:53,216 --> 00:29:57,082
and how extraordinary it
is to be eating like we are.

505
00:29:57,084 --> 00:29:58,684
I never take it off.

506
00:30:02,850 --> 00:30:06,683
Are you trying to get
me drunk? That's naughty.

507
00:30:07,682 --> 00:30:09,148
Just drink what you feel like.

508
00:30:09,150 --> 00:30:10,784
(WAITER SPEAKING FRENCH)

509
00:30:13,117 --> 00:30:15,048
The lamb and the veal are milk fed.

510
00:30:15,050 --> 00:30:17,983
This is the best time of the
year to eat young animals.

511
00:30:20,183 --> 00:30:24,150
Yes, well it's also the best
time to eat young carrots.

512
00:30:28,949 --> 00:30:32,951
So, why have you never married?

513
00:30:34,216 --> 00:30:36,148
I heard you had a girlfriend

514
00:30:36,150 --> 00:30:39,814
and she was a marvelous chef and
she had her own little restaurant.

515
00:30:39,816 --> 00:30:42,214
She sounded perfect for you.

516
00:30:42,216 --> 00:30:44,082
(INHALES DEEPLY)

517
00:30:44,084 --> 00:30:48,817
(SIGHS) Well, uh, that was a long time ago.

518
00:30:52,716 --> 00:30:54,983
Well, what happened?

519
00:30:55,950 --> 00:30:58,552
We were right for each other, but...

520
00:31:00,850 --> 00:31:03,817
Unfortunately, there were circumstances.

521
00:31:04,216 --> 00:31:05,648
Mmm-hmm.

522
00:31:05,650 --> 00:31:06,950
Not all things are meant to be.

523
00:31:08,217 --> 00:31:11,981
Yes, well, love isn't always fair.

524
00:31:11,983 --> 00:31:13,948
Why is that?

525
00:31:13,950 --> 00:31:15,883
It will never make sense to me.

526
00:31:25,816 --> 00:31:28,381
- ANNE: Jacques, I can't eat much more.
- (BOTH CHUCKLE)

527
00:31:28,383 --> 00:31:31,214
JACQUES: <i>This cheese is made
from unpasteurized milk.</i>

528
00:31:31,216 --> 00:31:33,082
<i>It's alive and very healthy.</i>

529
00:31:33,084 --> 00:31:35,814
Your cheese in America
is pasteurized. It's dead.

530
00:31:35,816 --> 00:31:38,115
It goes into your stomach
like a ball of fat.

531
00:31:38,117 --> 00:31:39,748
Is that why you French people can eat

532
00:31:39,750 --> 00:31:41,182
all the butter and cheese you want

533
00:31:41,184 --> 00:31:42,348
and never gain weight?

534
00:31:42,350 --> 00:31:44,282
Yes, and we drink more red wine.

535
00:31:44,284 --> 00:31:46,082
Of course, we are more romantic.

536
00:31:46,084 --> 00:31:47,950
Oh. Is that so?

537
00:31:49,817 --> 00:31:53,648
So, Brulee, you know my vice, it's smoking.

538
00:31:53,650 --> 00:31:55,651
Now you must confess yours.

539
00:32:00,216 --> 00:32:01,817
(INAUDIBLE)

540
00:32:05,316 --> 00:32:06,683
(BOTH LAUGHING)

541
00:32:07,716 --> 00:32:08,883
Oh, my gosh.

542
00:32:11,717 --> 00:32:15,047
That is the last time I
ever tell you the truth.

543
00:32:15,049 --> 00:32:16,083
Just taste.

544
00:32:17,716 --> 00:32:19,817
- Mmm.
- Just eat what you feel like.

545
00:32:20,616 --> 00:32:24,181
You know, unlike smoking,

546
00:32:24,183 --> 00:32:26,349
there are studies that say
that chocolate is good for you.

547
00:32:26,351 --> 00:32:27,982
(SCOFFS)

548
00:32:27,984 --> 00:32:31,148
You Americans always have to
have a reason for everything.

549
00:32:31,150 --> 00:32:33,015
We eat what we enjoy.

550
00:32:33,017 --> 00:32:34,617
Mmm. Mmm.

551
00:32:36,351 --> 00:32:40,382
Michael called me just before
we came down for dinner.

552
00:32:40,384 --> 00:32:43,584
He's worried about us here together.

553
00:32:44,116 --> 00:32:45,683
Are you?

554
00:32:47,617 --> 00:32:49,082
Should I be?

555
00:32:49,084 --> 00:32:50,249
Well, I don't know.

556
00:32:50,251 --> 00:32:54,083
In a long marriage, after
your child leaves home...

557
00:32:55,383 --> 00:32:56,850
Are you happy?

558
00:32:57,216 --> 00:32:58,550
Oh...

559
00:33:00,084 --> 00:33:00,882
We have a good marriage...

560
00:33:00,884 --> 00:33:02,551
No, that's not what I asked you.

561
00:33:03,217 --> 00:33:04,583
Are you happy?

562
00:33:05,984 --> 00:33:07,714
Well, sure.

563
00:33:07,716 --> 00:33:09,648
- Sometimes.
- (CHUCKLES)

564
00:33:09,650 --> 00:33:14,084
From Michael's call, I know
that he somehow mistrusts us.

565
00:33:17,716 --> 00:33:19,817
Perhaps he mistrusts himself.

566
00:33:22,717 --> 00:33:25,147
Is he faithful?

567
00:33:25,149 --> 00:33:30,349
Oh, well, you probably know better than I.

568
00:33:30,351 --> 00:33:33,115
He had quite a reputation and...

569
00:33:33,117 --> 00:33:35,147
Well, we went through some hard times.

570
00:33:35,149 --> 00:33:37,981
And have you made peace with your life?

571
00:33:37,983 --> 00:33:40,047
(CHUCKLES) What kind of question is that?

572
00:33:40,049 --> 00:33:42,014
I think it's a good question.

573
00:33:42,016 --> 00:33:44,081
Have you made peace with yourself

574
00:33:44,083 --> 00:33:46,815
and your marriage the way it is?

575
00:33:46,817 --> 00:33:47,515
Ah...

576
00:33:47,517 --> 00:33:50,215
- Oh.
- Don't worry, it's okay.

577
00:33:50,217 --> 00:33:52,583
I'm such a klutz.

578
00:33:53,284 --> 00:33:54,650
(SIGHS)

579
00:33:57,084 --> 00:34:00,282
We French, we have a different
attitude about marriage

580
00:34:00,284 --> 00:34:02,615
than you Americans.

581
00:34:02,617 --> 00:34:04,081
Oh, and what is that?

582
00:34:04,083 --> 00:34:05,614
We are practical.

583
00:34:05,616 --> 00:34:09,082
We're loyal to family and to marriage...

584
00:34:09,084 --> 00:34:13,118
But we are human, and we follow
our natural human passions.

585
00:34:15,016 --> 00:34:18,348
Well, we must seem
boringly puritanical to you.

586
00:34:18,350 --> 00:34:23,281
And guilty. Guilt is
bad for your digestion.

587
00:34:23,283 --> 00:34:27,047
Well, how would you say
Michael's digestion is? (SCOFFS)

588
00:34:27,049 --> 00:34:29,948
Well... (SIGHS) He's an attractive man,

589
00:34:29,950 --> 00:34:33,551
and women do outrageous
things to get into movies.

590
00:34:34,817 --> 00:34:40,814
Once, a wannabe starlet came
to our table at the beach.

591
00:34:40,816 --> 00:34:43,247
Michael had taken off his shoes.

592
00:34:43,249 --> 00:34:47,615
She picked one up, poured
champagne in it and toasted him.

593
00:34:47,617 --> 00:34:49,780
Michael felt her desperation.

594
00:34:49,782 --> 00:34:52,083
So, as he sent her away,

595
00:34:53,816 --> 00:34:56,783
he gave her his rose gold Rolex.

596
00:34:58,717 --> 00:35:00,118
He didn't have to do that.

597
00:35:06,351 --> 00:35:07,950
I gave him that watch.

598
00:35:10,616 --> 00:35:12,550
He told me he lost it.

599
00:35:13,783 --> 00:35:16,747
I'm sorry. I didn't mean to upset you.

600
00:35:16,749 --> 00:35:18,816
(FOOTSTEPS RECEDING)

601
00:35:27,216 --> 00:35:28,614
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

602
00:35:28,616 --> 00:35:30,683
(DOOR CREAKS OPENS)

603
00:35:34,084 --> 00:35:35,117
<i>Bonjour, madame.</i>

604
00:35:40,049 --> 00:35:41,083
<i>Bonjour.</i>

605
00:35:45,682 --> 00:35:48,683
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

606
00:35:49,649 --> 00:35:51,050
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

607
00:35:52,084 --> 00:35:53,683
(MUSIC PLAYING)

608
00:36:00,183 --> 00:36:01,681
(CHUCKLES)

609
00:36:01,683 --> 00:36:03,550
(SNIFFS AND SIGHS)

610
00:36:05,682 --> 00:36:06,917
(CELL PHONE CHIMES)

611
00:36:17,117 --> 00:36:18,118
(LINE RINGING)

612
00:36:20,083 --> 00:36:22,081
- SUZANNE: <i>Hey.</i>
- Hi.

613
00:36:22,083 --> 00:36:23,481
I didn't go.

614
00:36:23,483 --> 00:36:27,081
My ears were killing me, so Jacques
offered to drive me to Paris.

615
00:36:27,083 --> 00:36:28,847
<i>Excuse me? Jacques?</i>

616
00:36:28,849 --> 00:36:31,314
<i>Michael let you go with
a man named "Jacques"?</i>

617
00:36:31,316 --> 00:36:32,847
(SCOFFS)

618
00:36:32,849 --> 00:36:34,581
Suzanne, come on. Michael trusts me.

619
00:36:34,583 --> 00:36:38,948
<i>You're driving across France with
Jacques, and you didn't call me?</i>

620
00:36:38,950 --> 00:36:40,614
<i>When are you picking me up?</i>

621
00:36:40,616 --> 00:36:42,281
(LAUGHS)

622
00:36:42,283 --> 00:36:45,747
He's a flirt. And he eats
too much and he smokes.

623
00:36:45,749 --> 00:36:48,783
<i>So do I. We're perfect
for each other.</i>

624
00:36:49,616 --> 00:36:52,147
<i>Is he adorable?</i>

625
00:36:52,149 --> 00:36:56,914
Yeah. But I came on this trip
to spend some time with Michael.

626
00:36:56,916 --> 00:36:59,681
<i>Yeah, and look where you are.</i>

627
00:36:59,683 --> 00:37:01,047
<i>Seize the moment.</i>

628
00:37:01,049 --> 00:37:02,781
<i>Just make sure he doesn't leave you</i>

629
00:37:02,783 --> 00:37:04,246
<i>stranded along the road somewhere.</i>

630
00:37:04,248 --> 00:37:06,082
Yeah, right.

631
00:37:06,084 --> 00:37:08,084
- <i>Gotta go.</i>
- Bye.

632
00:37:10,916 --> 00:37:11,917
(CHUCKLES)

633
00:37:48,983 --> 00:37:50,814
Good morning, Brulee.

634
00:37:50,816 --> 00:37:52,648
So, how are you feeling?

635
00:37:52,650 --> 00:37:54,281
Much better, thank you.

636
00:37:54,283 --> 00:37:55,981
My earache's nearly gone thanks
to those marvelous ear drops.

637
00:37:55,983 --> 00:37:59,313
And the medicinal quality
of fine French wine.

638
00:37:59,315 --> 00:38:01,082
Ha! No doubt.

639
00:38:01,084 --> 00:38:03,148
And the hot chocolate was a
very nice touch, thank you.

640
00:38:03,150 --> 00:38:05,381
I haven't had any hot
chocolate for breakfast

641
00:38:05,383 --> 00:38:07,314
since I was at Girl Scout camp.

642
00:38:07,316 --> 00:38:08,947
How did you sleep?

643
00:38:08,949 --> 00:38:09,848
Oh, well.

644
00:38:09,850 --> 00:38:12,647
I noticed you're not wearing any socks.

645
00:38:12,649 --> 00:38:15,815
Oh, yes. You see everything.

646
00:38:15,817 --> 00:38:18,247
I didn't pack any so I washed the ones

647
00:38:18,249 --> 00:38:19,948
I was wearing, but they are not dry.

648
00:38:19,950 --> 00:38:22,181
Well, I happen to have some of Michael's.

649
00:38:22,183 --> 00:38:24,213
He left them at the hotel.

650
00:38:24,215 --> 00:38:25,982
Would you like them?

651
00:38:25,984 --> 00:38:27,381
Yeah.

652
00:38:27,383 --> 00:38:29,783
Oh, well, why not. Thanks.

653
00:38:31,783 --> 00:38:35,213
I know what it means to walk in
another man's shoes, but his socks?

654
00:38:35,215 --> 00:38:36,584
(CHUCKLES)

655
00:38:37,382 --> 00:38:39,084
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

656
00:38:43,216 --> 00:38:44,246
(KEYS JANGLING)

657
00:38:44,248 --> 00:38:46,615
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

658
00:38:46,617 --> 00:38:50,081
I'd like to pay for my room last night.

659
00:38:50,083 --> 00:38:53,280
Actually, I need your credit
card, if you don't mind.

660
00:38:53,282 --> 00:38:54,814
- Again?
- Yes.

661
00:38:54,816 --> 00:38:57,615
I discovered my envelope
of cash went back to Paris

662
00:38:57,617 --> 00:38:59,680
with my assistant by mistake.

663
00:38:59,682 --> 00:39:04,084
So I had to leave the charges of
our rooms and dinner on your card.

664
00:39:06,215 --> 00:39:07,714
Okay.

665
00:39:07,716 --> 00:39:09,281
You know, my name is
quite common in France,

666
00:39:09,283 --> 00:39:13,380
and unfortunately, someone
using the same name has been

667
00:39:13,382 --> 00:39:15,815
charging on false cards.

668
00:39:15,817 --> 00:39:17,881
Until it is fixed, I have to use cash.

669
00:39:17,883 --> 00:39:22,880
I have enough for gas and little
things, but not for hotel and dinner.

670
00:39:22,882 --> 00:39:25,881
I will reimburse you as
soon as we get to Paris.

671
00:39:25,883 --> 00:39:26,883
Right.

672
00:39:27,882 --> 00:39:29,246
Okay.

673
00:39:29,248 --> 00:39:30,314
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

674
00:39:30,316 --> 00:39:31,684
(CELL PHONE RINGS)

675
00:39:33,215 --> 00:39:34,550
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

676
00:39:44,749 --> 00:39:46,081
So I have good news.

677
00:39:46,083 --> 00:39:48,347
My friend got us a
lunch reservation in Lyon

678
00:39:48,349 --> 00:39:51,914
at the restaurant with a new chef
who's got outstanding reviews.

679
00:39:51,916 --> 00:39:53,180
Jacques, that sounds wonderful,

680
00:39:53,182 --> 00:39:55,314
but I thought we'd be in Paris by now.

681
00:39:55,316 --> 00:39:58,081
Paris can wait.

682
00:39:58,083 --> 00:40:01,747
We can't leave without
taking a look at the pyramid,

683
00:40:01,749 --> 00:40:03,281
as they call it here.

684
00:40:03,283 --> 00:40:05,614
Of course not.

685
00:40:05,616 --> 00:40:07,614
(ANNE LAUGHS)

686
00:40:07,616 --> 00:40:09,551
- (CAR THUDS)
- (ANNE GRUNTS)

687
00:40:10,115 --> 00:40:12,247
Huh!

688
00:40:12,249 --> 00:40:17,046
Two-thousand years ago this marked
the center of a Roman circus.

689
00:40:17,048 --> 00:40:20,081
Can you feel the chariots racing

690
00:40:20,083 --> 00:40:21,714
right here where we're standing?

691
00:40:21,716 --> 00:40:23,584
- That's so amazing!
- Yeah.

692
00:40:25,216 --> 00:40:26,814
- Come.
- Wait.

693
00:40:26,816 --> 00:40:30,983
It's not really a
pyramid, but, it's more...

694
00:40:32,316 --> 00:40:34,651
- ANNE: Obelisk?
- Yes.

695
00:40:35,182 --> 00:40:36,348
Wow.

696
00:40:36,350 --> 00:40:38,551
Birds live in here. (CHUCKLES)

697
00:40:40,617 --> 00:40:41,814
ANNE: Do you play "I Spy"?

698
00:40:41,816 --> 00:40:43,681
JACQUES: Sounds dangerous.

699
00:40:43,683 --> 00:40:45,982
ANNE: It's a game I used to play
with Alexandra on road trips.

700
00:40:45,984 --> 00:40:47,081
(COW MOOING)

701
00:40:47,083 --> 00:40:49,817
I spy something with four legs.

702
00:40:51,817 --> 00:40:54,783
I spy something with two lovely legs.

703
00:40:55,883 --> 00:40:56,982
Come on.

704
00:40:56,984 --> 00:40:58,083
Game over.

705
00:40:59,082 --> 00:41:00,784
Not yet.

706
00:41:02,148 --> 00:41:03,683
(MUSIC PLAYING)

707
00:41:51,982 --> 00:41:52,983
(EXASPERATED SIGH)

708
00:42:01,649 --> 00:42:03,750
- Where the hell have you been?
- Oh!

709
00:42:05,049 --> 00:42:09,117
A friend lives very nearby.
She has a garden full of roses.

710
00:42:12,083 --> 00:42:13,083
Excuse me.

711
00:42:13,982 --> 00:42:15,917
Please, come in.

712
00:42:17,216 --> 00:42:18,550
Uh...

713
00:42:21,049 --> 00:42:24,080
We'll have their perfume
until the rest of our trip.

714
00:42:24,082 --> 00:42:25,982
ANNE: (CHUCKLES) Mmm.

715
00:42:29,182 --> 00:42:30,683
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

716
00:42:31,649 --> 00:42:33,348
Ready?

717
00:42:33,350 --> 00:42:34,684
(SPEAKS ITALIAN)

718
00:42:36,016 --> 00:42:37,584
(MUSIC PLAYING)

719
00:42:53,115 --> 00:42:56,347
This is a perfect time to be
traveling through this region.

720
00:42:56,349 --> 00:42:58,381
The Rhone River is nearby.

721
00:42:58,383 --> 00:43:01,614
We can turn off and have a look.

722
00:43:01,616 --> 00:43:04,113
Are we ever going to get to Paris?

723
00:43:04,115 --> 00:43:06,816
Let's pretend we have a year to get there.

724
00:43:07,982 --> 00:43:09,684
(SINGING IN FRENCH)

725
00:43:20,349 --> 00:43:22,348
Most of the people don't realize

726
00:43:22,350 --> 00:43:24,381
there are many delicious things to eat

727
00:43:24,383 --> 00:43:26,783
growing right under their noses.

728
00:43:29,349 --> 00:43:30,681
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

729
00:43:30,683 --> 00:43:32,950
Look, it's wild fennel.

730
00:43:34,148 --> 00:43:37,714
Catch a trout, grill it on a bed of that,

731
00:43:37,716 --> 00:43:39,614
and you have something really...

732
00:43:39,616 --> 00:43:40,680
(LOUD BANG)

733
00:43:40,682 --> 00:43:42,751
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

734
00:43:43,315 --> 00:43:44,683
(JAQCUES EXCLAIMING)

735
00:43:52,817 --> 00:43:53,981
JACQUES: (SIGHS) Oh, my God!

736
00:43:53,983 --> 00:43:54,881
What?

737
00:43:54,883 --> 00:43:56,949
I have no idea what's wrong. (CHUCKLES)

738
00:43:58,848 --> 00:43:59,981
(SIGHS)

739
00:43:59,983 --> 00:44:02,949
But look where we are, in
this beautiful countryside!

740
00:44:04,716 --> 00:44:06,016
Let's have a picnic!

741
00:44:07,316 --> 00:44:09,080
What?

742
00:44:09,082 --> 00:44:12,615
Jacques, I need to get to
Paris, and we have a problem.

743
00:44:12,617 --> 00:44:15,047
Our problem isn't going anywhere.

744
00:44:15,049 --> 00:44:17,648
I brought a few things from the hotel.

745
00:44:17,650 --> 00:44:18,983
- Come on.
- (CELL PHONE RINGING)

746
00:44:19,717 --> 00:44:20,883
(ANNE CHUCKLES)

747
00:44:25,083 --> 00:44:27,347
Alex, honey,

748
00:44:27,349 --> 00:44:30,814
is everything all right? It's
the middle of the night there.

749
00:44:30,816 --> 00:44:32,380
ALEXANDRA: (DEJECTEDLY) <i>Mom.</i>

750
00:44:32,382 --> 00:44:34,083
What, what's the matter?

751
00:44:34,848 --> 00:44:37,648
<i>Noah is such a jerk!</i>

752
00:44:37,650 --> 00:44:38,947
What? What, what, what?

753
00:44:38,949 --> 00:44:40,714
<i>He finally asks me to hang out,</i>

754
00:44:40,716 --> 00:44:42,147
<i>so, like, I meet him at Dugan's Pub,</i>

755
00:44:42,149 --> 00:44:44,946
<i>and he brings his
two stoner roommates.</i>

756
00:44:44,948 --> 00:44:48,380
Honey, he was probably just nervous.

757
00:44:48,382 --> 00:44:51,381
Boys don't always know what
they're doing, not even big boys.

758
00:44:51,383 --> 00:44:54,113
Sometimes you need to take the lead.

759
00:44:54,115 --> 00:44:55,946
<i>That's so lame.</i>

760
00:44:55,948 --> 00:44:58,949
May I remind you, this is
a great time in your life?

761
00:45:00,082 --> 00:45:01,982
<i>Mom, I hear birds.</i>

762
00:45:02,616 --> 00:45:04,681
