what it takes to finish them.

813
00:47:57,649 --> 00:47:58,983
I think you do.

814
00:48:00,248 --> 00:48:03,180
You know, let's pretend we
are in that Manet painting,

815
00:48:03,182 --> 00:48:04,913
<i>Le dejeuner sur l'herbe.</i>

816
00:48:04,915 --> 00:48:06,081
Oh.

817
00:48:06,083 --> 00:48:07,083
Right.

818
00:48:09,049 --> 00:48:10,050
(ANNE CHUCKLES)

819
00:48:21,949 --> 00:48:24,313
See? The car is still waiting.

820
00:48:24,315 --> 00:48:26,116
Now we have a problem.

821
00:48:29,315 --> 00:48:30,683
Ah...

822
00:48:31,982 --> 00:48:34,613
I don't think it's the radiator.

823
00:48:34,615 --> 00:48:35,880
I wouldn't know.

824
00:48:35,882 --> 00:48:37,381
Well, of course you wouldn't know.

825
00:48:37,383 --> 00:48:39,083
There's nothing to eat under here.

826
00:48:41,681 --> 00:48:43,749
Oh, my God.

827
00:48:48,082 --> 00:48:49,083
ANNE: A-ha!

828
00:48:52,082 --> 00:48:53,980
Fan belt!

829
00:48:53,982 --> 00:48:55,749
Well, yeah.

830
00:48:58,948 --> 00:49:00,779
Do you have your pocket knife?

831
00:49:00,781 --> 00:49:01,782
Yeah.

832
00:49:02,681 --> 00:49:04,081
All right, here. Hold this.

833
00:49:04,083 --> 00:49:05,083
Turn around.

834
00:49:07,083 --> 00:49:08,550
Turn around.

835
00:49:12,149 --> 00:49:16,814
Once I saw a woman on YouTube doing this.

836
00:49:16,816 --> 00:49:19,149
It looked simple at the time.

837
00:49:20,349 --> 00:49:21,713
Here.

838
00:49:21,715 --> 00:49:23,281
Take that side.

839
00:49:23,283 --> 00:49:24,815
- That one.
- Okay.

840
00:49:25,916 --> 00:49:27,682
Okay, cut it where your thumb is.

841
00:49:29,616 --> 00:49:30,981
All right.

842
00:49:30,983 --> 00:49:32,114
Right over left.

843
00:49:32,116 --> 00:49:33,213
I hope I did that right.

844
00:49:33,215 --> 00:49:34,582
(JACQUES CHUCKLES)

845
00:49:36,382 --> 00:49:38,246
All right, you're gonna have to fit this

846
00:49:38,248 --> 00:49:40,647
around where the fan belt goes.

847
00:49:40,649 --> 00:49:42,081
- The...
- Try it.

848
00:49:42,083 --> 00:49:43,847
Uh, where?

849
00:49:43,849 --> 00:49:45,946
Well, it's gotta go under the thing.

850
00:49:45,948 --> 00:49:48,147
- Okay, okay, I can see.
- Around the other side.

851
00:49:48,149 --> 00:49:49,779
It's gotta go over the whole thing.

852
00:49:49,781 --> 00:49:51,682
- Now it's too loose.
- (SIGHS)

853
00:49:53,316 --> 00:49:54,816
I need your knife again.

854
00:49:57,949 --> 00:50:00,081
All right, I think I got that right.

855
00:50:00,083 --> 00:50:01,847
Maybe not.

856
00:50:01,849 --> 00:50:02,850
Okay.

857
00:50:05,083 --> 00:50:06,550
Try that.

858
00:50:07,148 --> 00:50:08,149
(EXHALES)

859
00:50:11,083 --> 00:50:12,914
- All the way. Is it all the way?
- Yeah.

860
00:50:12,916 --> 00:50:15,683
It's okay. Let's see if actually it works.

861
00:50:23,849 --> 00:50:25,682
(CAR ENGINE STALLING)

862
00:50:29,282 --> 00:50:31,549
(ENGINE STARTS)

863
00:50:32,782 --> 00:50:34,680
You American women are ingenious!

864
00:50:34,682 --> 00:50:36,016
(BOTH LAUGH)

865
00:50:48,749 --> 00:50:50,649
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

866
00:50:54,282 --> 00:50:55,983
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

867
00:50:59,715 --> 00:51:01,780
What's he say?

868
00:51:01,782 --> 00:51:03,680
He said, "You're a very clever woman."

869
00:51:03,682 --> 00:51:07,750
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

870
00:51:15,082 --> 00:51:16,083
(EXHALES)

871
00:51:21,216 --> 00:51:26,680
Now, let's pretend we're driving
straight to Paris in a car that works.

872
00:51:26,682 --> 00:51:29,679
And we don't need another thing
to eat or drink for a month.

873
00:51:29,681 --> 00:51:32,814
This car is designed to
make you lose your appetite.

874
00:51:32,816 --> 00:51:36,083
Well, it has airbags.
And I can play my music.

875
00:51:38,848 --> 00:51:41,613
I'm sure you know this
band. They're French.

876
00:51:41,615 --> 00:51:44,746
Alex gave this to me. She saw
them play at the Hollywood Bowl.

877
00:51:44,748 --> 00:51:46,582
- Yes, it's Phoenix.
- (ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

878
00:51:47,083 --> 00:51:48,214
(SIGHS)

879
00:51:48,216 --> 00:51:49,913
(SPEAKS ITALIAN)

880
00:51:49,915 --> 00:51:51,048
Ha-ha!

881
00:51:51,050 --> 00:51:53,149
Oh, I just hope my car
can rise from the ashes.

882
00:51:56,616 --> 00:52:00,880
<i>♪ Everything is everything ♪</i>

883
00:52:00,882 --> 00:52:03,213
<i>♪ The more I talk about it ♪</i>

884
00:52:03,215 --> 00:52:05,313
<i>♪ The less I do control ♪</i>

885
00:52:05,315 --> 00:52:09,813
<i>♪ Everything means everything ♪</i>

886
00:52:09,815 --> 00:52:12,047
<i>♪ Can't understand a word ♪</i>

887
00:52:12,049 --> 00:52:14,113
<i>♪ Half of the stuff I'm sayin' ♪</i>

888
00:52:14,115 --> 00:52:17,312
JACQUES: Well, this is Lyon.

889
00:52:17,314 --> 00:52:20,046
We are in the heart of France.

890
00:52:20,048 --> 00:52:24,613
So how far are we from Paris? Be honest.

891
00:52:24,615 --> 00:52:26,782
Not far. We have a stop first.

892
00:52:37,615 --> 00:52:40,247
Well, this is L'Institut Lumiere,

893
00:52:40,249 --> 00:52:42,780
and the two Lumiere
brothers, they lived here

894
00:52:42,782 --> 00:52:45,679
when they invented cinematography.

895
00:52:45,681 --> 00:52:47,117
The director is a friend of mine.

896
00:52:49,216 --> 00:52:50,549
Jacques!

897
00:52:51,648 --> 00:52:53,583
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

898
00:53:07,348 --> 00:53:11,214
Anne has come all the way from
America to see your museum.

899
00:53:11,216 --> 00:53:12,312
Well.

900
00:53:12,314 --> 00:53:13,613
Almost.

901
00:53:13,615 --> 00:53:14,880
I'm Anne.

902
00:53:14,882 --> 00:53:16,646
Martine.

903
00:53:16,648 --> 00:53:18,750
Well, let's go, then.

904
00:53:20,815 --> 00:53:22,582
(JACQUES SPEAKING FRENCH)

905
00:53:25,248 --> 00:53:27,117
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

906
00:53:33,216 --> 00:53:37,081
Anne, Martine and I
have business to discuss,

907
00:53:37,083 --> 00:53:40,214
so, she organized a tour for you.

908
00:53:40,216 --> 00:53:41,714
- Oh.
- Yeah.

909
00:53:41,716 --> 00:53:43,779
Philippe will show you our museum.

910
00:53:43,781 --> 00:53:45,080
Hi, nice to meet you.

911
00:53:45,082 --> 00:53:46,647
Nice to meet you.

912
00:53:46,649 --> 00:53:48,017
Right this way, please.

913
00:53:51,816 --> 00:53:53,550
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

914
00:53:57,314 --> 00:53:59,946
GUIDE: Then we'll move to this one.

915
00:53:59,948 --> 00:54:02,312
This is, uh, the Cinematographe,

916
00:54:02,314 --> 00:54:04,347
which is the very first camera.

917
00:54:04,349 --> 00:54:08,312
It was invented by Louis
and Auguste Lumiere in 1895.

918
00:54:08,314 --> 00:54:09,949
It is also a projector.

919
00:54:23,949 --> 00:54:28,879
And then you have a model of
the first public projection.

920
00:54:28,881 --> 00:54:34,813
And the Lumiere brothers, um,
thought their invention had no future.

921
00:54:34,815 --> 00:54:37,714
- Apparently they were wrong.
- (CHUCKLES)

922
00:54:37,716 --> 00:54:39,614
Well, that concludes our tour.

923
00:54:39,616 --> 00:54:41,346
Thank you.

924
00:54:41,348 --> 00:54:45,213
Um, I'm sorry, I have to go, but
you're free to visit the gift shop.

925
00:54:45,215 --> 00:54:47,682
- Have a nice day.
- Thank you.

926
00:55:04,247 --> 00:55:05,815
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

927
00:55:13,214 --> 00:55:14,947
- Hi.
- Hi.

928
00:55:14,949 --> 00:55:16,782
Martine is joining us for lunch.

929
00:55:17,214 --> 00:55:18,583
Oh.

930
00:55:20,682 --> 00:55:24,212
On the way I'll show you the
best market in all of France.

931
00:55:24,214 --> 00:55:25,280
Oh...

932
00:55:25,282 --> 00:55:26,650
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

933
00:55:32,949 --> 00:55:34,679
- Sausage from here.
- Mmm. Thank you.

934
00:55:34,681 --> 00:55:37,014
- Very good. It's the best one.
- Mmm.

935
00:55:37,016 --> 00:55:39,746
JACQUES: <i>And look, the
very best ingredients.</i>

936
00:55:39,748 --> 00:55:41,949
<i>All the chefs come here.</i>

937
00:55:43,282 --> 00:55:45,080
Wonderful!

938
00:55:45,082 --> 00:55:49,213
You know that there used to
be worms in, uh, old cheese?

939
00:55:49,215 --> 00:55:51,946
- Worms? In the cheese?
- Mmm-hmm. Mmm-hmm.

940
00:55:51,948 --> 00:55:54,347
So you had in the same
time cheese and the meat.

941
00:55:54,349 --> 00:55:56,347
(BOTH LAUGH)

942
00:55:56,349 --> 00:56:00,212
JACQUES: This family has been
selling cheese for over 200 years.

943
00:56:00,214 --> 00:56:03,380
Look at <i>les fromages de
chevre.</i> This is goat cheese.

944
00:56:03,382 --> 00:56:06,246
There is so many different kinds.

945
00:56:06,248 --> 00:56:09,616
<i>My favorite is, uh,
Crottin de Chavignol.</i>

946
00:56:10,081 --> 00:56:11,145
Anne.

947
00:56:11,147 --> 00:56:12,148
(MARTINE SPEAKING FRENCH)

948
00:56:13,082 --> 00:56:14,680
Thank you.

949
00:56:14,682 --> 00:56:16,613
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

950
00:56:16,615 --> 00:56:17,947
Be my guest.

951
00:56:17,949 --> 00:56:18,747
(ANNE LAUGHS)

952
00:56:18,749 --> 00:56:20,312
- It's great, no?
- BOTH WOMEN: Mmm.

953
00:56:20,314 --> 00:56:22,549
- No worms.
- No worms.

954
00:56:29,349 --> 00:56:30,715
(SIGHS)

955
00:56:31,682 --> 00:56:32,849
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

956
00:56:36,115 --> 00:56:37,616
Please.

957
00:56:39,081 --> 00:56:40,279
It's tasty, no?

958
00:56:40,281 --> 00:56:43,847
You know, they found fava
beans in the Egyptian tombs.

959
00:56:43,849 --> 00:56:44,913
Hmm.

960
00:56:44,915 --> 00:56:47,879
Jacques, remember those
divine fava beans we had

961
00:56:47,881 --> 00:56:51,180
in that marvelous little place in Palermo?

962
00:56:51,182 --> 00:56:52,550
Mmm.

963
00:56:53,681 --> 00:56:55,947
Mmm. And in Sardinia, we had pureed favas

964
00:56:55,949 --> 00:56:59,082
served with those delicious
wild bitter greens.

965
00:56:59,882 --> 00:57:00,950
Hmm? Hmm.

966
00:57:02,816 --> 00:57:04,014
It seems to me that the two of you

967
00:57:04,016 --> 00:57:06,013
would like a chance to catch up.

968
00:57:06,015 --> 00:57:08,746
And I'm not very hungry, so I
think I'm gonna take a little walk.

969
00:57:08,748 --> 00:57:10,112
- No, no.
- Oh, no, no, it's fine.

970
00:57:10,114 --> 00:57:12,180
- Please, please, sit down.
- No, you two catch up.

971
00:57:12,182 --> 00:57:15,950
Absolutely not. You've got to
taste this food. Please, sit down.

972
00:57:18,082 --> 00:57:19,082
All right.

973
00:57:21,815 --> 00:57:24,313
- (EXHALES SLOWLY)
- JACQUES: Ah.

974
00:57:24,315 --> 00:57:25,683
(SPEAKS FRENCH)

975
00:57:28,114 --> 00:57:29,115
Escargot.

976
00:57:30,615 --> 00:57:33,380
Here, these are delicious.

977
00:57:33,382 --> 00:57:35,346
Mmm. They've changed chefs,

978
00:57:35,348 --> 00:57:36,613
but the snails are still good.

979
00:57:36,615 --> 00:57:38,747
JACQUES: Mmm, mmm, mmm.

980
00:57:38,749 --> 00:57:41,814
JACQUES: You must never
cook a dead snail, never.

981
00:57:41,816 --> 00:57:44,346
They must always be cooked alive.

982
00:57:44,348 --> 00:57:46,045
- It's true.
- It's a nightmare

983
00:57:46,047 --> 00:57:48,246
